I would personally advise using flex as this results in more consistent results.
The elements are positioned from left to right in the order that they appear in the container; so your left element is first, and then your right element. All the `.left and .right` classes are doing in colouring the divs and setting how wide you would like them.

**Example:**
&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    .left {
      width: 80%;
      background: #500;
    }

    .right {
      width: 20%;
      background: #005;
    }

    .container {
      width: 100%;
      height: 100px;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: row;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;container&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;left&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;right&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

I&#39;m not confident what the precise issue is, but my assumption is subpixel widths. If you look at the width of the `left` `div`, the white gap usually appears when there is a pixel value of `.49px` or below (eg: `1034.19px`) but is fine if the pixel value is `.5px` or above.

I would suggest trying to use CSS grid, it appears to also resolve this issue:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

    body {
      margin: 0;
    }

    .grid {
      width: 100%;
      position: fixed;
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 4fr 1fr;
    }

    .left,
    .right {
      height: 100px;
    }

    .left {
      background: #500;
    }

    .right {
      background: #005;
    }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;

    &lt;div class=&quot;grid&quot;&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;left&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;div class=&quot;right&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

